h2. Workaround

Use the External System Import for the moment (Requires Administrative permission).

{{g + g > External System Import > CSV Import}}

One of our projects is titled "Intranet" and has the key "IN", so if it appears unquoted in JQL it will produce a syntax error.

After importing a batch of issues using the CSV import feature, the link to "Check created issues" uses the following JQL:
{code}
project=IN AND issuekey>=IN-868 AND issuekey<=IN-875 AND creator=currentUser()
{code}

Which results in an error:
{quote}
Error in JQL Query: Expecting either a value, list or function but got 'IN'. You must surround 'IN' in quotation marks to use it as a value. (line 1, character 9)
{quote}

Correcting to the following works:
{code}
project="IN" AND issuekey>=IN-868 AND issuekey<=IN-875 AND creator=currentUser()
{code}

It appears the payload of /rest/webhooks/1.0/webhook/ has changed with 7.0, and I can't find any documentation to support this change. For example, posting something like the follow creates a webhook

{code}
{
"name":"Test Webhook 4",
"url":"http://www.testsite.com/webhooks",
"events":["jira:issue_updated"],
"jqlFilter": "project=ABC"
}
{code}

But, the results from the endpoint when you query it seem to have changed from 6.x to 7.x. 

{code}
[
 ...
  {
    "name": "Test Webhook 4",
    "url": "http://www.testsite.com/webhooks",
    "excludeBody": false,
    "filters": {
      "issue-related-events-section": ""
    },
    "events": [
      "jira:issue_updated"
    ],
    "enabled": true,
    ...
  }
]
{code}

The {{filters}} property appears to used to be called {{filter}} and was a single string.

Here's an example:

{code}
Add blah to the {{Foo::*::Request}} classes *right now*.
{code}

This should render as

{code}
<p>Add blah to the <tt>Foo::*::Request</tt> classes <strong>right now</strong>.</p>
{code}

Instead, it renders as

{code}
<p>Add blah to the <tt>Foo::<b>::Request</b></tt><b> classes *right now</b>.</p>
{code}

Seems nuts to me. would be nice to have markup for {{<code>}} elements in addition to {{<tt>}}; maybe the handling of markup internal to it can be different from the {{<tt>}} markup, but I would argue that even what's there now is pretty weird.

